SIMPLE: invest
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Invest
<hw>In*vest"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Invested</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Investing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>investire</ets>,
<ets>investitum</ets>; pref. <ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>vestire</ets> to
clothe, fr. <ets>vestis</ets> clothing: cf. F. <ets>investir</ets>. See
<er>Vest</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To put garments on; to clothe; to dress; to array;
-- opposed to <ant>divest</ant>. Usually followed by <xex>with</xex>,
sometimes by <xex>in</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>invest</ex> one with a
robe</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put on.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Can not find one this girdle to <qex>invest</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To clothe, as with office or authority; to place in
possession of rank, dignity, or estate; to endow; to adorn; to grace; to
bedeck; <as>as, to <ex>invest</ex> with honor or glory; to
<ex>invest</ex> with an estate.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I do <qex>invest</qex> you jointly with my power.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To surround, accompany, or attend.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Awe such as must always <qex>invest</qex> the spectacle of the
guilt.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To confer; to give.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It <qex>investeth</qex> a right of government.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>To inclose; to surround or hem in
with troops, so as to intercept reinforcements of men and provisions and
prevent escape; to lay siege to; <as>as, to <ex>invest</ex> a
town</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To lay out (money or capital) in business with the
view of obtaining an income or profit; <as>as, to <ex>invest</ex> money
in bank stock</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>To expend (time, money, or
other resources) with a view to obtaining some benefit of value in
excess of that expended, or to achieve a useful pupose; <as>as, to
<ex>invest</ex> a lot of time in teaching one's children</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Invest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Invest
<hw>In*vest"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make an
investment; <as>as, to <ex>invest</ex> in stocks</as>; -- usually
followed by <xex>in</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Investient</ent>⟦br⟧
